{
  "doc_id": "14339",
  "text": "There is also good evidence that RNA regulates chromatin architecture. DNA methylation is RNA-directed, at least in plants and probably in all higher eukaryotes [CITATION_1] . The phenomenon of transvection, or allelic cross-talk, which has been largely described in Drosophila but which also occurs in other higher eukaryotes [CITATION_2] , has been implicated in genomic imprinting and X chromosome inactivation and almost certainly involves trans-acting RNA signals (see [CITATION_3] ). Transvection, co-suppression and transgene silencing have all been shown to involve Polycombgroup proteins [CITATION_4] , which are involved in chromatin remodeling via histone deacetylation [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , leading to the suggestion that trans-acting RNAs may direct the gene-specific binding of Polycomb complexes (Sharp, 2001) .",
